ics and meanings of kinship</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I007822/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>&lt;br />Dr Jennifer Speirs has been awarded an ESRC Postdoctoral Fellowship to disseminate and develop the policy and academic findings of the doctoral research which explored social aspects of anonymous semen donation in the UK and built upon insights into what makes people relatives, the social construction of connectedness and meanings of the 'gift'. It examined the views of men who donated semen when they were medical students, between 25 and 45 years ago, and how they perceive the influence of the passing years on their understandings of kinship and on the meaning and significance of their donations. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The project examines also the continuing disputes about secrecy and anonymity amongst infertility treatment provision stakeholders in the UK and their relationship to beliefs about parenthood.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Dr Speirs will be based at Edinburgh University's Centre for Research on Families and Relationship (CRFR), and will organise a joint CRFR/Innogen Research Centre symposium on 'inheritance', disseminate research findings to policy makers, to academics in social science, law and bioethics and to practising counsellors, social workers and infertility treatment providers, and produce briefing papers, seminar presentations at Edinburgh and the Charles University Prague, and papers at international conferences for social anthropologists and social workers.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>82113</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>IFSW2015 Poster</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>International</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>B2BC6CC3-A02F-482A-B82D-A27417E8DC6A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>I presented a poster entitled 'Are my partner's donor offspring related to me?' at the International Federation of Social Workers European Biennial conference in Glasgow. The poster data was derived from a small piece of research carried out during my postdoctoral fellowship.The poster was seen by numerous people and some engaged in discussion about the issues.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>58c7157f103fb4.98262778</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2015</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Member of Church of Scotland's Society Religion and 